  "content": [
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Clinical Setting"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Febrile, regional, painful lymphadenitis (Buboes). Regional lymph nodes become enlarged and tender; inguinal lymph nodes are most common. Result of bite of infected rodent flea. If untreated can progress to bacteremia, with and without shock, and seeding of lungs and rarely meninges."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Diagnosis"
    },
    {
      "type": "diagnosticTest",
      "diagnosticTestData": {
        "name": "Antigen detection or PCR",
        "notes": "Fastest method."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "diagnosticTest",
      "diagnosticTestData": {
        "name": "Stain of aspirate from Bubo (suppurative node)",
        "interpretation": "With proper staining has bipolar appearance like a closed clothes pin."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Etiologies"
    },
    {
